<list id="lectureoverview" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic"><item>Three stages of social choice:
(a) Deciding how to decide how to decide (forming a group identity), (b) Deciding how to decide (choosing a constitution, and rules), (c) Deciding (normal choices, using fixed rules)</item>
  <item>Access rules (introducing a bill, Writ of Certiorari, moved and seconded, etc) require less than a majority.</item>
  <item>Decision rules usually (but not always) require a majority</item>
  <item>Changing the rules requires a supermajority</item>
  <item>Constituting a group requires unanimous consent, or (what amounts to the same thing) a means of exiting. Forced entry into membership is actually a restriction on exit.</item>
  <item>Arrow's Theorem</item>
  <item>An example: Interest Groups--The National Rifle Association</item>
  <item>Rousseau, and Buchanan-Tullock, and "optimal majority."</item>
  <item>Borda Count: Examples of ways of choosing</item>
</list></para></section><section id="eip-278"><title>Readings</title><para id="eip-411"><list id="readinglist"><item>Munger-Munger, <emphasis effect="italics">Choosing in Groups</emphasis>, Chapter 7</item>
